The paper deals with geometric algorithms and optimization problems in the Euclidean plane, which suggests that it belongs to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of graph theory and approximation algorithms also suggests that it could belong to the data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The study of structural properties of minimum spanning trees and the analysis of ratios of edge lengths suggest that it could belong to the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. The use of numerical methods and optimization techniques suggests that it could belong to the numerical analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. Finally, the study of approximation algorithms and the analysis of bounds suggest that it could belong to the game theory and economics (cs.GT) sub-category.
